04580nam a22005655i 9780774868365DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748683657 a10.59962/97807748683652doi  a(DE-B1597)671302  a(OCoLC)1408681313  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE78.C2bP43 2023 7aHIS0060402bisacsh04a971.3004/9734009033qOCoLC223/eng/202311201 aPeace, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Slow Rush of Colonization :bSpaces of Power in the Maritime Peninsula, 1680–1790 /cThomas Peace. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (350 p.) :b2 b&w photos, 9 maps, 1 diagram, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tSawantaun, the Maritime Peninsula, and Settler Colonialism -- tSpaces of Power -- tSeeking Legitimacy -- tAn Imperial Periphery -- tLimited Relationships -- tImperial Transitions and Consolidations of Power -- tProtecting Spaces of Power -- tGeographies of Solidarity -- tReimagining Spaces of Power -- tThe Logic of Settler Conquest -- tFrom Settler Conquest to Settler Colonialism -- tSawantaun, Survivance, and the Slow Rush of Colonization -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1760, after Montcalm’s defeat at the Plains of Abraham, the French Empire was definitively expelled from the Saint Lawrence Valley. This history is well known. Less well known is that this decisive victory had its roots almost a hundred years earlier, when settler colonial systems of power first took root on the peripheries of the Maritime Peninsula (the places known today as Quebec, Maritime Canada, and New England). Drawing on the concept of spaces of power, historian Thomas Peace demonstrates that despite imperial changes of power and settler colonial incursions on their Lands, local Mi’kmaw, Wabanaki, Peskotomuhkati, Wolastoqiyik, and Wendat nations continued to experience the contested Peninsula as a cohesive whole, rather than one defined by subsequent colonial borders. This engaging history shows how overlapping concepts of space and power – shaped deeply by Indigenous agency and diplomacy – defined relationships in the eighteenth-century Maritime Peninsula and how, following the Seven Years’ War, this history was brushed aside as settlers flooded into the Peninsula, laying the groundwork from which Canada and the United States would develop.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndigenous peopleszAtlantic Coast (North America)xHistoryy18th century. 0aIndigenous peopleszAtlantic Coast (North America)xPolitics and governmentxHistoryy18th century. 0aIndigenous peopleszAtlantic Coast (North America)xSocial conditionsy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Provincial, Territorial & Local / Atlantic Provinces (NB, NL, NS, PE).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311140824840uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486836540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774868365423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774868365/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-140824-8  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  